<!-- The document content area with serialized nodes -->

<TextWithNodes><Node id="0" />SSL International<Node id="17" />, which is being investigated by the <Node id="54" />Serious Fraud Office<Node id="74" /> for overstating its results, is to replace <Node id="118" />Arthur Andersen<Node id="133" />, the auditors under fire from some investors for failing to spot the irregularity.<Node id="216" />

<Node id="218" />The healthcare group, which makes Durex condoms and Scholl sandals, has put the audit contract up for tender.<Node id="327" />

<Node id="329" />Arthur Andersen<Node id="344" /> has not been invited to reapply and is not being considered.<Node id="405" />

<Node id="407" />It declined to comment on <Node id="433" />Thursday<Node id="441" />, but is expected to say it is departing by mutual agreement.<Node id="502" />

<Node id="504" />It is said to be expressing confidence privately that the <Node id="562" />SFO<Node id="565" /> investigation will vindicate it.<Node id="598" />

<Node id="600" />SSL<Node id="603" /> said on <Node id="612" />Thursday<Node id="620" />: "The process to appoint an auditor is well under way" but declined to comment further.<Node id="708" />

<Node id="710" />People close to the company said <Node id="743" />Andersen<Node id="751" /> had not put its name forward but even if it had it would have been extremely unlikely to have been selected.<Node id="860" />

<Node id="862" />Replacing the auditors will mark another important change at <Node id="923" />SSL<Node id="926" />, which over the <Node id="943" />past year<Node id="952" /> has seen the departure of its finance director, chief executive, two other executive directors and the planned retirement of its chairman.<Node id="1091" />

<Node id="1093" />The auditors were attacked by private investors at <Node id="1144" />last month<Node id="1154" />'s annual meeting for failing to detect that <Node id="1199" />SSL<Node id="1202" /> had overstated sales by <Node id="1227" />£22m<Node id="1231" /> (<Node id="1233" />$31m<Node id="1237" />) and profits before tax and exceptionals by <Node id="1282" />£19m<Node id="1286" /> in the <Node id="1294" />1999<Node id="1298" /> and <Node id="1303" />2000 financial years<Node id="1323" />.<Node id="1324" />

<Node id="1326" />About 100 investors voted against the board's proposal to retain <Node id="1391" />Arthur Anderse<Node id="1405" />n but were defeated by a large margin by institutional investors who backed the proposal.<Node id="1494" />

<Node id="1496" />However, <Node id="1505" />Stuart Wallis<Node id="1518" />, <Node id="1520" />SSL<Node id="1523" />'s chairman, told the meeting that the company would put the audit contract, which was worth <Node id="1616" />£700,000<Node id="1624" /> <Node id="1625" />last year<Node id="1634" />, up for tender.<Node id="1650" />

<Node id="1652" />The company said the overstatement appeared to have been caused by a complex fraud.<Node id="1735" />

<Node id="1737" />On <Node id="1740" />Wednesday<Node id="1749" />, the <Node id="1755" />SFO<Node id="1758" /> launched an investigation into whether <Node id="1798" />SSL<Node id="1801" /> employees or former employees might have committed criminal offences.<Node id="1871" />

<Node id="1873" />The <Node id="1877" />SFO<Node id="1880" /> has studied the findings of an investigation by <Node id="1929" />KPMG<Node id="1933" />, the professional services firm, and <Node id="1971" />DLA<Node id="1974" />, a law firm, which were called in by <Node id="2012" />Gary Watts<Node id="2022" />, <Node id="2024" />SSL<Node id="2027" />'s finance director.<Node id="2047" />

<Node id="2049" />The inquiry found the results were overstated through the use of fake invoices, goods that never reached customers, and inflated exceptional costs.<Node id="2196" />
